ce:section.ce:para:
CDs prepared from different sources are widely explored in metal ion sensing. Thus, we subjected our CDs for sensing the following metal ions, Na+, K+, Co2+, Cd2+, Sn2+, Ni2+, Pb2+, Ca2+, Zn2+, Hg2+, Cu2+, Mn2+, Mg2+, Ba2+, Al3+, Bi3+, Fe3+, Cr3+, Au3+, Ag+ [38–41]. Unlike other reports, our CDs fluorescence was not affected by any of the described metal ions, but the fluorescence of CDs containing Ag+ and Au3+ diminished slowly over the time (12 h) with subsequent change in the color. Ag+ solution turns yellow and Au3+ solution turns purple, which remains stable, i.e., without precipitating for more than a month. Analyzing these solutions in UV–visible spectroscopy revealed a characteristic surface plasmon resonance (SPR) of silver nanoparticles (AgNPs) and gold nanoparticles (AuNPs). The SPR maximum of AgNPs were observed at 410 nm and AuNPs were observed at 520 nm (Fig. 6
                     ). Energy dispersive X-ray (EDX) spectrum confirmed the presence of elemental silver and gold in the respective solutions. The morphology and size determined from transmission electron microscopy (TEM) image showed that AgNPs are spherical with size range from 8 to 22 nm and AuNPs are spherical with size range from 5 to 15 nm. High resolution TEM showed lattice fringe patterns with d-spacing of 0.23 nm and selected area electron diffraction (SAED) displays a set of concentric ring, suggesting that the AgNPs and AuNPs are crystalline in nature (Fig. 7
                     ). The control experiments performed by adding Ag+ and Au3+ to CE showed no color change for more than 48 h, indicating the inability of CE to form NPs. These results suggest CDs derived from CE has the ability to reduce Ag+ to AgNPs and Au3+ to AuNPs and also stabilize them against aggregation.

The anticipated use of the AgNPs and AuNPs as efficient catalyst was evaluated through studying nitroaromatic reduction kinetics. The catalytic hydrogenation of 4-nitrophenol (4-NP) was followed by UV–visible spectroscopy (Fig. 8
                     ). Typically, the addition of reducing agent, sodium borohydride to 4-NP showed an absorption peak maximum at 400 nm which remains unaltered for hours. However, the addition of either AgNPs or AuNPs to this mixture resulted in hypochromic and hypsochromic shift, indicating the reduction of 4-NP (Fig. 8A). During this reduction reaction the color of the 4-NP turns from pale yellow to yellow and then ends colorless, suggesting that the chromophore -NO2 gets reduced to -NH2. Time dependent hypochromic shift at 400 nm was used to investigate the reduction kinetics (Fig. 8B). Before proceeding to hypochromic shift, an induction time (t0) was observed. This t0 was attributed to the restructuring or activation of 4-NP on the catalyst surface or the time required by the catalyst to bring down dissolved oxygen level below the critical value [42,43]. After t0, the absorbance at 400 nm decreases dramatically and stops changing, indicating that the 4-NP is converted to the product, 4-aminophenol. Excess NaBH4 was used in this reaction that the substrate, thus, the reduction kinetics was described by pseudo-first order rate equation. Fitting the linear portion of the kinetic trace by the equation, ln(At/A0) = −kt, yielded the apparent first-order rate constant (k) (Table 1
                     ). In this equation, t is the reaction time, At and A0 are the absorbance of the substrate at time t and 0, respectively. The scope of the prepared nanocatalyst was extended to other nitroaromatic compounds and the results are presented in Table 1. Although there is a significant difference in the induction period, the rate constant determined for all the tested nitroaromatic compounds are in the order of 10−2 s−1, which is consistent with the chemical reactions that are catalyzed by substrate-supported metallic nanoparticles [35].
